erature, and provincial life. The Europeanization of the Russian elite paradoxically strengthened its pride in its Russianness, precisely because it participated in networks of interaction and exchange with European elites and shared in their linguistic and cultural capital. In this way, Europeanization generated forms of sociability that helped the elite consolidate its corporate identity as distinct from court society and also from the people. The Europeanization of Russia was uniquely intense, complex, and pervasive, as it aimed not only to emulate forms of behavior, but to forge an elite that was intrinsically European, while remaining Russian. The second of a two-volume project (the first is a multi-authored collection of case studies), this insightful study will appeal to scholars and students of Russian and East European history and culture, as well as those interested in transnational processes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aElite (Social sciences)zRussiaxHistoryy18th century. 0aElite (Social sciences)zRussiaxHistoryy19th century. 4aHistory. 4aSoviet & East European History. 4aWest European History. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  aRussian history, Europeanization of Russia, Russian class, Russian elites.1 aZorin, Andrei, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060655340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150175736540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501757365423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501757365/original  a978-3-11-060655-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL